ation?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Most 1099 loan programs require historical 1099 income documentation rather than projected future earnings. Lenders base qualification on demonstrated earning patterns from previous tax years, not anticipated future income. However, if your most recent year shows significant income growth, underwriters may give additional consideration to the upward trend."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do business ownership percentages affect qualification?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "If you own a business that pays you via 1099 rather than W-2 wages, the ownership structure becomes relevant. Lenders may examine whether you're essentially self-employed through your own entity or truly an independent contractor for a separate business. The distinction affects documentation requirements and income calculation methodology."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What if you have gaps in 1099 income?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Employment gaps or periods without 1099 income require explanation and can impact qualification depending on duration and circumstances. Short gaps between contracts\u2014common in independent contractor work\u2014typically don't disqualify you when overall income patterns demonstrate consistency."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can foreign nationals qualify for a 1099 loan?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Foreign national borrowers earning 1099 income in the United States may qualify for specialized 1099 loan programs depending on visa status, income documentation, and lender guidelines. The combination of non-citizen status and self-employment income requires careful program selection."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How does cost of goods sold affect 1099 income qualification?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Some independent contractors incur direct costs of goods sold (COGS) that differ from general business expenses. F